57bool Qualifiers::isStrictSupersetOf(Qualifiers Other) const {
58 return (*this != Other) &&
59 // CVR qualifiers superset
60 (((Mask & CVRMask) | (Other.Mask & CVRMask)) == (Mask & CVRMask)) &&
61 // ObjC GC qualifiers superset
62 ((getObjCGCAttr() == Other.getObjCGCAttr()) ||
63 (hasObjCGCAttr() && !Other.hasObjCGCAttr())) &&
64 // Address space superset.
65 ((getAddressSpace() == Other.getAddressSpace()) ||
66 (hasAddressSpace()&& !Other.hasAddressSpace())) &&
67 // Lifetime qualifier superset.
68 ((getObjCLifetime() == Other.getObjCLifetime()) ||
69 (hasObjCLifetime() && !Other.hasObjCLifetime()));
70}

72const IdentifierInfo* QualType::getBaseTypeIdentifier() const {
73 const Type* ty = getTypePtr();
74 NamedDecl *ND = nullptr;
75 if (ty->isPointerType() || ty->isReferenceType())
76 return ty->getPointeeType().getBaseTypeIdentifier();
77 else if (ty->isRecordType())
78 ND = ty->getAs<RecordType>()->getDecl();
79 else if (ty->isEnumeralType())
80 ND = ty->getAs<EnumType>()->getDecl();
81 else if (ty->getTypeClass() == Type::Typedef)
82 ND = ty->getAs<TypedefType>()->getDecl();
83 else if (ty->isArrayType())
84 return ty->castAsArrayTypeUnsafe()->
85 getElementType().getBaseTypeIdentifier();
86
87 if (ND)
88 return ND->getIdentifier();
89 return nullptr;
90}

102bool QualType::isConstant(QualType T, const ASTContext &Ctx) {
103 if (T.isConstQualified())
104 return true;
105
106 if (const ArrayType *AT = Ctx.getAsArrayType(T))
107 return AT->getElementType().isConstant(Ctx);
108
109 return T.getAddressSpace() == LangAS::opencl_constant;
110}

112unsigned ConstantArrayType::getNumAddressingBits(const ASTContext &Context,
113 QualType ElementType,
114 const llvm::APInt &NumElements) {
115 uint64_t ElementSize = Context.getTypeSizeInChars(ElementType).getQuantity();
116
117 // Fast path the common cases so we can avoid the conservative computation
118 // below, which in common cases allocates "large" APSInt values, which are
119 // slow.
120
121 // If the element size is a power of 2, we can directly compute the additional
122 // number of addressing bits beyond those required for the element count.
123 if (llvm::isPowerOf2_64(ElementSize)) {
124 return NumElements.getActiveBits() + llvm::Log2_64(ElementSize);
125 }
126
127 // If both the element count and element size fit in 32-bits, we can do the
128 // computation directly in 64-bits.
129 if ((ElementSize >> 32) == 0 && NumElements.getBitWidth() <= 64 &&
130 (NumElements.getZExtValue() >> 32) == 0) {
131 uint64_t TotalSize = NumElements.getZExtValue() * ElementSize;
132 return 64 - llvm::countLeadingZeros(TotalSize);
133 }
134
135 // Otherwise, use APSInt to handle arbitrary sized values.
136 llvm::APSInt SizeExtended(NumElements, true);
137 unsigned SizeTypeBits = Context.getTypeSize(Context.getSizeType());
138 SizeExtended = SizeExtended.extend(std::max(SizeTypeBits,
139 SizeExtended.getBitWidth()) * 2);
140
141 llvm::APSInt TotalSize(llvm::APInt(SizeExtended.getBitWidth(), ElementSize));
142 TotalSize *= SizeExtended;
143
144 return TotalSize.getActiveBits();
145}
146
147unsigned ConstantArrayType::getMaxSizeBits(const ASTContext &Context) {
148 unsigned Bits = Context.getTypeSize(Context.getSizeType());
149
150 // Limit the number of bits in size_t so that maximal bit size fits 64 bit
151 // integer (see PR8256). We can do this as currently there is no hardware
152 // that supports full 64-bit virtual space.
153 if (Bits > 61)
154 Bits = 61;
155
156 return Bits;
157}

259/// getArrayElementTypeNoTypeQual - If this is an array type, return the
260/// element type of the array, potentially with type qualifiers missing.
261/// This method should never be used when type qualifiers are meaningful.
262const Type *Type::getArrayElementTypeNoTypeQual() const {
263 // If this is directly an array type, return it.
264 if (const auto *ATy = dyn_cast<ArrayType>(this))
265 return ATy->getElementType().getTypePtr();
266
267 // If the canonical form of this type isn't the right kind, reject it.
268 if (!isa<ArrayType>(CanonicalType))
269 return nullptr;
270
271 // If this is a typedef for an array type, strip the typedef off without
272 // losing all typedef information.
273 return cast<ArrayType>(getUnqualifiedDesugaredType())
274 ->getElementType().getTypePtr();
275}
276
277/// getDesugaredType - Return the specified type with any "sugar" removed from
278/// the type. This takes off typedefs, typeof's etc. If the outer level of
279/// the type is already concrete, it returns it unmodified. This is similar
280/// to getting the canonical type, but it doesn't remove *all* typedefs. For
281/// example, it returns "T*" as "T*", (not as "int*"), because the pointer is
282/// concrete.
283QualType QualType::getDesugaredType(QualType T, const ASTContext &Context) {
284 SplitQualType split = getSplitDesugaredType(T);
285 return Context.getQualifiedType(split.Ty, split.Quals);
286}
287
288QualType QualType::getSingleStepDesugaredTypeImpl(QualType type,
289 const ASTContext &Context) {
290 SplitQualType split = type.split();
291 QualType desugar = split.Ty->getLocallyUnqualifiedSingleStepDesugaredType();
292 return Context.getQualifiedType(desugar, split.Quals);
293}
294
295// Check that no type class is polymorphic. LLVM style RTTI should be used
296// instead. If absolutely needed an exception can still be added here by
297// defining the appropriate macro (but please don't do this).
298#define TYPE(CLASS, BASE) \
299 static_assert(!std::is_polymorphic<CLASS##Type>::value, \
300 #CLASS "Type should not be polymorphic!");
301#include "clang/AST/TypeNodes.def"
302
303QualType Type::getLocallyUnqualifiedSingleStepDesugaredType() const {
304 switch (getTypeClass()) {
305#define ABSTRACT_TYPE(Class, Parent)
306#define TYPE(Class, Parent) \
307 case Type::Class: { \
308 const auto *ty = cast<Class##Type>(this); \
309 if (!ty->isSugared()) return QualType(ty, 0); \
310 return ty->desugar(); \
311 }
312#include "clang/AST/TypeNodes.def"
313 }
314 llvm_unreachable("bad type kind!");
315}
316
317SplitQualType QualType::getSplitDesugaredType(QualType T) {
318 QualifierCollector Qs;
319
320 QualType Cur = T;
321 while (true) {
322 const Type *CurTy = Qs.strip(Cur);
323 switch (CurTy->getTypeClass()) {
324#define ABSTRACT_TYPE(Class, Parent)
325#define TYPE(Class, Parent) \
326 case Type::Class: { \
327 const auto *Ty = cast<Class##Type>(CurTy); \
328 if (!Ty->isSugared()) \
329 return SplitQualType(Ty, Qs); \
330 Cur = Ty->desugar(); \
331 break; \
332 }
333#include "clang/AST/TypeNodes.def"
334 }
335 }
336}
337
338SplitQualType QualType::getSplitUnqualifiedTypeImpl(QualType type) {
339 SplitQualType split = type.split();
340
341 // All the qualifiers we've seen so far.
342 Qualifiers quals = split.Quals;
343
344 // The last type node we saw with any nodes inside it.
345 const Type *lastTypeWithQuals = split.Ty;
346
347 while (true) {
348 QualType next;
349
350 // Do a single-step desugar, aborting the loop if the type isn't
351 // sugared.
352 switch (split.Ty->getTypeClass()) {
353#define ABSTRACT_TYPE(Class, Parent)
354#define TYPE(Class, Parent) \
355 case Type::Class: { \
356 const auto *ty = cast<Class##Type>(split.Ty); \
357 if (!ty->isSugared()) goto done; \
358 next = ty->desugar(); \
359 break; \
360 }
361#include "clang/AST/TypeNodes.def"
362 }
363
364 // Otherwise, split the underlying type. If that yields qualifiers,
365 // update the information.
366 split = next.split();
367 if (!split.Quals.empty()) {
368 lastTypeWithQuals = split.Ty;
369 quals.addConsistentQualifiers(split.Quals);
370 }
371 }
372
373 done:
374 return SplitQualType(lastTypeWithQuals, quals);
375}

377QualType QualType::IgnoreParens(QualType T) {
378 // FIXME: this seems inherently un-qualifiers-safe.
379 while (const auto *PT = T->getAs<ParenType>())
380 T = PT->getInnerType();
381 return T;
382}
383
384/// This will check for a T (which should be a Type which can act as
385/// sugar, such as a TypedefType) by removing any existing sugar until it
386/// reaches a T or a non-sugared type.
387template<typename T> static const T *getAsSugar(const Type *Cur) {
388 while (true) {
389 if (const auto *Sugar = dyn_cast<T>(Cur))
390 return Sugar;
391 switch (Cur->getTypeClass()) {
392#define ABSTRACT_TYPE(Class, Parent)
393#define TYPE(Class, Parent) \
394 case Type::Class: { \
395 const auto *Ty = cast<Class##Type>(Cur); \
396 if (!Ty->isSugared()) return 0; \
397 Cur = Ty->desugar().getTypePtr(); \
398 break; \
399 }
400#include "clang/AST/TypeNodes.def"
401 }
402 }
403}

417/// getUnqualifiedDesugaredType - Pull any qualifiers and syntactic
418/// sugar off the given type. This should produce an object of the
419/// same dynamic type as the canonical type.
420const Type *Type::getUnqualifiedDesugaredType() const {
421 const Type *Cur = this;
422
423 while (true) {
424 switch (Cur->getTypeClass()) {
425#define ABSTRACT_TYPE(Class, Parent)
426#define TYPE(Class, Parent) \
427 case Class: { \
428 const auto *Ty = cast<Class##Type>(Cur); \
429 if (!Ty->isSugared()) return Cur; \
430 Cur = Ty->desugar().getTypePtr(); \
431 break; \
432 }
433#include "clang/AST/TypeNodes.def"
434 }
435 }
436}

470bool Type::isCHERICapabilityType(const ASTContext &Context,
471 bool IncludeIntCap) const {
472 if (const PointerType *PT = getAs<PointerType>())
473 return PT->isCHERICapability();
474 else if (const ReferenceType *RT = getAs<ReferenceType>())
475 return RT->isCHERICapability();
476 else if (isObjCObjectPointerType() || isBlockPointerType())
477 return Context.getTargetInfo().areAllPointersCapabilities();
478 else if (const EnumType *ET = getAs<EnumType>()) {
479 QualType Ty = ET->getDecl()->getIntegerType();
480 return Ty.isNull() ? false
481 : Ty->isCHERICapabilityType(Context, IncludeIntCap);
482 } else if (const BuiltinType *BT = getAs<BuiltinType>()) {
483 auto Kind = BT->getKind();
484 if (Kind == BuiltinType::IntCap ||
485 Kind == BuiltinType::UIntCap)
486 return IncludeIntCap;
487 if (Kind == BuiltinType::ObjCId || Kind == BuiltinType::NullPtr)
488 return Context.getTargetInfo().areAllPointersCapabilities();
489 } else if (const AtomicType *AT = getAs<AtomicType>())
490 return AT->getValueType()->isCHERICapabilityType(Context, IncludeIntCap);
491 else if (const MemberPointerType *MPT = getAs<MemberPointerType>())
492 // XXXAR: Currently member function pointers contain capabities, but
493 // pointers to member data don't
494 return Context.getTargetInfo().areAllPointersCapabilities() && MPT->isMemberFunctionPointer();
495 return false;
496}
497
498bool Type::isIntCapType() const {
499 if (const BuiltinType *BT = dyn_cast<BuiltinType>(CanonicalType))
500 return BT->getKind() == BuiltinType::IntCap ||
501 BT->getKind() == BuiltinType::UIntCap;
502 // Also handle enums with underlying type __intcap_t
503 if (const EnumType *ET = dyn_cast<EnumType>(CanonicalType)) {
504 QualType Ty = ET->getDecl()->getIntegerType();
505 if (!Ty.isNull())
506 return Ty->isIntCapType();
507 }
508 return false;
509}

547QualType Type::getPointeeType() const {
548 if (const auto *PT = getAs<PointerType>())
549 return PT->getPointeeType();
550 if (const auto *OPT = getAs<ObjCObjectPointerType>())
551 return OPT->getPointeeType();
552 if (const auto *BPT = getAs<BlockPointerType>())
553 return BPT->getPointeeType();
554 if (const auto *RT = getAs<ReferenceType>())
555 return RT->getPointeeType();
556 if (const auto *MPT = getAs<MemberPointerType>())
557 return MPT->getPointeeType();
558 if (const auto *DT = getAs<DecayedType>())
559 return DT->getPointeeType();
560 return {};
561}

563const RecordType *Type::getAsStructureType() const {
564 // If this is directly a structure type, return it.
565 if (const auto *RT = dyn_cast<RecordType>(this)) {
566 if (RT->getDecl()->isStruct())
567 return RT;
568 }
569
570 // If the canonical form of this type isn't the right kind, reject it.
571 if (const auto *RT = dyn_cast<RecordType>(CanonicalType)) {
572 if (!RT->getDecl()->isStruct())
573 return nullptr;
574
575 // If this is a typedef for a structure type, strip the typedef off without
576 // losing all typedef information.
577 return cast<RecordType>(getUnqualifiedDesugaredType());
578 }
579 return nullptr;
580}
581
582const RecordType *Type::getAsUnionType() const {
583 // If this is directly a union type, return it.
584 if (const auto *RT = dyn_cast<RecordType>(this)) {
585 if (RT->getDecl()->isUnion())
586 return RT;
587 }
588
589 // If the canonical form of this type isn't the right kind, reject it.
590 if (const auto *RT = dyn_cast<RecordType>(CanonicalType)) {
591 if (!RT->getDecl()->isUnion())
592 return nullptr;
593
594 // If this is a typedef for a union type, strip the typedef off without
595 // losing all typedef information.
596 return cast<RecordType>(getUnqualifiedDesugaredType());
597 }
598
599 return nullptr;
600}
601
602bool Type::isObjCIdOrObjectKindOfType(const ASTContext &ctx,
603 const ObjCObjectType *&bound) const {
604 bound = nullptr;
605
606 const auto *OPT = getAs<ObjCObjectPointerType>();
607 if (!OPT)
608 return false;
609
610 // Easy case: id.
611 if (OPT->isObjCIdType())
612 return true;
613
614 // If it's not a __kindof type, reject it now.
615 if (!OPT->isKindOfType())
616 return false;
617
618 // If it's Class or qualified Class, it's not an object type.
619 if (OPT->isObjCClassType() || OPT->isObjCQualifiedClassType())
620 return false;
621
622 // Figure out the type bound for the __kindof type.
623 bound = OPT->getObjectType()->stripObjCKindOfTypeAndQuals(ctx)
624 ->getAs<ObjCObjectType>();
625 return true;
626}
627
628bool Type::isObjCClassOrClassKindOfType() const {
629 const auto *OPT = getAs<ObjCObjectPointerType>();
630 if (!OPT)
631 return false;
632
633 // Easy case: Class.
634 if (OPT->isObjCClassType())
635 return true;
636
637 // If it's not a __kindof type, reject it now.
638 if (!OPT->isKindOfType())
639 return false;
640
641 // If it's Class or qualified Class, it's a class __kindof type.
642 return OPT->isObjCClassType() || OPT->isObjCQualifiedClassType();
643}

655
656ObjCObjectType::ObjCObjectType(QualType Canonical, QualType Base,
657 ArrayRef<QualType> typeArgs,
658 ArrayRef<ObjCProtocolDecl *> protocols,
659 bool isKindOf)
660 : Type(ObjCObject, Canonical, Base->isDependentType(),
661 Base->isInstantiationDependentType(),
662 Base->isVariablyModifiedType(),
663 Base->containsUnexpandedParameterPack()),
664 BaseType(Base) {
665 ObjCObjectTypeBits.IsKindOf = isKindOf;
666
667 ObjCObjectTypeBits.NumTypeArgs = typeArgs.size();
668 assert(getTypeArgsAsWritten().size() == typeArgs.size() &&
669 "bitfield overflow in type argument count");
670 if (!typeArgs.empty())
671 memcpy(getTypeArgStorage(), typeArgs.data(),
672 typeArgs.size() * sizeof(QualType));
673
674 for (auto typeArg : typeArgs) {
675 if (typeArg->isDependentType())
676 setDependent();
677 else if (typeArg->isInstantiationDependentType())
678 setInstantiationDependent();
679
680 if (typeArg->containsUnexpandedParameterPack())
681 setContainsUnexpandedParameterPack();
682 }
683 // Initialize the protocol qualifiers. The protocol storage is known
684 // after we set number of type arguments.
685 initialize(protocols);
686}
687
688bool ObjCObjectType::isSpecialized() const {
689 // If we have type arguments written here, the type is specialized.
690 if (ObjCObjectTypeBits.NumTypeArgs > 0)
691 return true;
692
693 // Otherwise, check whether the base type is specialized.
694 if (const auto objcObject = getBaseType()->getAs<ObjCObjectType>()) {
695 // Terminate when we reach an interface type.
696 if (isa<ObjCInterfaceType>(objcObject))
697 return false;
698
699 return objcObject->isSpecialized();
700 }
701
702 // Not specialized.
703 return false;
704}
705
706ArrayRef<QualType> ObjCObjectType::getTypeArgs() const {
707 // We have type arguments written on this type.
708 if (isSpecializedAsWritten())
709 return getTypeArgsAsWritten();
710
711 // Look at the base type, which might have type arguments.
712 if (const auto objcObject = getBaseType()->getAs<ObjCObjectType>()) {
713 // Terminate when we reach an interface type.
714 if (isa<ObjCInterfaceType>(objcObject))
715 return {};
716
717 return objcObject->getTypeArgs();
718 }
719
720 // No type arguments.
721 return {};
722}
723
724bool ObjCObjectType::isKindOfType() const {
725 if (isKindOfTypeAsWritten())
726 return true;
727
728 // Look at the base type, which might have type arguments.
729 if (const auto objcObject = getBaseType()->getAs<ObjCObjectType>()) {
730 // Terminate when we reach an interface type.
731 if (isa<ObjCInterfaceType>(objcObject))
732 return false;
733
734 return objcObject->isKindOfType();
735 }
736
737 // Not a "__kindof" type.
738 return false;
739}
740
741QualType ObjCObjectType::stripObjCKindOfTypeAndQuals(
742 const ASTContext &ctx) const {
743 if (!isKindOfType() && qual_empty())
744 return QualType(this, 0);
745
746 // Recursively strip __kindof.
747 SplitQualType splitBaseType = getBaseType().split();
748 QualType baseType(splitBaseType.Ty, 0);
749 if (const auto *baseObj = splitBaseType.Ty->getAs<ObjCObjectType>())
750 baseType = baseObj->stripObjCKindOfTypeAndQuals(ctx);
751
752 return ctx.getObjCObjectType(ctx.getQualifiedType(baseType,
753 splitBaseType.Quals),
754 getTypeArgsAsWritten(),
755 /*protocols=*/{},
756 /*isKindOf=*/false);
757}
758
759const ObjCObjectPointerType *ObjCObjectPointerType::stripObjCKindOfTypeAndQuals(
760 const ASTContext &ctx) const {
761 if (!isKindOfType() && qual_empty())
762 return this;
763
764 QualType obj = getObjectType()->stripObjCKindOfTypeAndQuals(ctx);
765 return ctx.getObjCObjectPointerType(obj)->castAs<ObjCObjectPointerType>();
766}

770/// Visitor used to perform a simple type transformation that does not change
771/// the semantics of the type.
772template <typename Derived>
773struct SimpleTransformVisitor : public TypeVisitor<Derived, QualType> {
774 ASTContext &Ctx;
775
776 QualType recurse(QualType type) {
777 // Split out the qualifiers from the type.
778 SplitQualType splitType = type.split();
779
780 // Visit the type itself.
781 QualType result = static_cast<Derived *>(this)->Visit(splitType.Ty);
782 if (result.isNull())
783 return result;
784
785 // Reconstruct the transformed type by applying the local qualifiers
786 // from the split type.
787 return Ctx.getQualifiedType(result, splitType.Quals);
788 }
789
790public:
791 explicit SimpleTransformVisitor(ASTContext &ctx) : Ctx(ctx) {}
792
793 // None of the clients of this transformation can occur where
794 // there are dependent types, so skip dependent types.
795#define TYPE(Class, Base)
796#define DEPENDENT_TYPE(Class, Base) \
797 QualType Visit##Class##Type(const Class##Type *T) { return QualType(T, 0); }
798#include "clang/AST/TypeNodes.def"
799
800#define TRIVIAL_TYPE_CLASS(Class) \
801 QualType Visit##Class##Type(const Class##Type *T) { return QualType(T, 0); }
802#define SUGARED_TYPE_CLASS(Class) \
803 QualType Visit##Class##Type(const Class##Type *T) { \
804 if (!T->isSugared()) \
805 return QualType(T, 0); \
806 QualType desugaredType = recurse(T->desugar()); \
807 if (desugaredType.isNull()) \
808 return {}; \
809 if (desugaredType.getAsOpaquePtr() == T->desugar().getAsOpaquePtr()) \
810 return QualType(T, 0); \
811 return desugaredType; \
812 }
813
814 TRIVIAL_TYPE_CLASS(Builtin)
815
816 QualType VisitComplexType(const ComplexType *T) {
817 QualType elementType = recurse(T->getElementType());
818 if (elementType.isNull())
819 return {};
820
821 if (elementType.getAsOpaquePtr() == T->getElementType().getAsOpaquePtr())
822 return QualType(T, 0);
823
824 return Ctx.getComplexType(elementType);
825 }
826
827 QualType VisitPointerType(const PointerType *T) {
828 QualType pointeeType = recurse(T->getPointeeType());
829 if (pointeeType.isNull())
830 return {};
831
832 if (pointeeType.getAsOpaquePtr() == T->getPointeeType().getAsOpaquePtr())
833 return QualType(T, 0);
834
835 return Ctx.getPointerType(pointeeType);
836 }
837
838 QualType VisitBlockPointerType(const BlockPointerType *T) {
839 QualType pointeeType = recurse(T->getPointeeType());
840 if (pointeeType.isNull())
841 return {};
842
843 if (pointeeType.getAsOpaquePtr() == T->getPointeeType().getAsOpaquePtr())
844 return QualType(T, 0);
845
846 return Ctx.getBlockPointerType(pointeeType);
847 }
848
849 QualType VisitLValueReferenceType(const LValueReferenceType *T) {
850 QualType pointeeType = recurse(T->getPointeeTypeAsWritten());
851 if (pointeeType.isNull())
852 return {};
853
854 if (pointeeType.getAsOpaquePtr()
855 == T->getPointeeTypeAsWritten().getAsOpaquePtr())
856 return QualType(T, 0);
857
858 return Ctx.getLValueReferenceType(pointeeType, T->isSpelledAsLValue());
859 }
860
861 QualType VisitRValueReferenceType(const RValueReferenceType *T) {
862 QualType pointeeType = recurse(T->getPointeeTypeAsWritten());
863 if (pointeeType.isNull())
864 return {};
865
866 if (pointeeType.getAsOpaquePtr()
867 == T->getPointeeTypeAsWritten().getAsOpaquePtr())
868 return QualType(T, 0);
869
870 return Ctx.getRValueReferenceType(pointeeType);
871 }
872

874 QualType pointeeType = recurse(T->getPointeeType());
875 if (pointeeType.isNull())
876 return {};
877
878 if (pointeeType.getAsOpaquePtr() == T->getPointeeType().getAsOpaquePtr())
879 return QualType(T, 0);
880
881 return Ctx.getMemberPointerType(pointeeType, T->getClass());
882 }
883

885 QualType elementType = recurse(T->getElementType());
886 if (elementType.isNull())
887 return {};
888

890 return QualType(T, 0);
891

893 T->getSizeModifier(),
894 T->getIndexTypeCVRQualifiers());
895 }

913 if (elementType.isNull())
914 return {};
915
916 if (elementType.getAsOpaquePtr() == T->getElementType().getAsOpaquePtr())
917 return QualType(T, 0);
918
919 return Ctx.getIncompleteArrayType(elementType, T->getSizeModifier(),
920 T->getIndexTypeCVRQualifiers());
921 }

926 return {};
927

937 if (elementType.isNull())
938 return {};
939
940 if (elementType.getAsOpaquePtr() == T->getElementType().getAsOpaquePtr())
941 return QualType(T, 0);
942
943 return Ctx.getExtVectorType(elementType, T->getNumElements());
944 }
945
946 QualType VisitFunctionNoProtoType(const FunctionNoProtoType *T) {
947 QualType returnType = recurse(T->getReturnType());
948 if (returnType.isNull())
949 return {};
950
951 if (returnType.getAsOpaquePtr() == T->getReturnType().getAsOpaquePtr())
952 return QualType(T, 0);
953
954 return Ctx.getFunctionNoProtoType(returnType, T->getExtInfo());
955 }
956
957 QualType VisitFunctionProtoType(const FunctionProtoType *T) {
958 QualType returnType = recurse(T->getReturnType());
959 if (returnType.isNull())
960 return {};
961
962 // Transform parameter types.
963 SmallVector<QualType, 4> paramTypes;
964 bool paramChanged = false;
965 for (auto paramType : T->getParamTypes()) {
966 QualType newParamType = recurse(paramType);
967 if (newParamType.isNull())
968 return {};
969
970 if (newParamType.getAsOpaquePtr() != paramType.getAsOpaquePtr())
971 paramChanged = true;
972
973 paramTypes.push_back(newParamType);
974 }
975
976 // Transform extended info.
977 FunctionProtoType::ExtProtoInfo info = T->getExtProtoInfo();
978 bool exceptionChanged = false;
979 if (info.ExceptionSpec.Type == EST_Dynamic) {
980 SmallVector<QualType, 4> exceptionTypes;
981 for (auto exceptionType : info.ExceptionSpec.Exceptions) {
982 QualType newExceptionType = recurse(exceptionType);
983 if (newExceptionType.isNull())
984 return {};
985
986 if (newExceptionType.getAsOpaquePtr() != exceptionType.getAsOpaquePtr())
987 exceptionChanged = true;
988
989 exceptionTypes.push_back(newExceptionType);
990 }
991
992 if (exceptionChanged) {
993 info.ExceptionSpec.Exceptions =
994 llvm::makeArrayRef(exceptionTypes).copy(Ctx);
995 }
996 }
997
998 if (returnType.getAsOpaquePtr() == T->getReturnType().getAsOpaquePtr() &&
999 !paramChanged && !exceptionChanged)
1000 return QualType(T, 0);
1001
1002 return Ctx.getFunctionType(returnType, paramTypes, info);
1003 }
1004
1005 QualType VisitParenType(const ParenType *T) {
1006 QualType innerType = recurse(T->getInnerType());
1007 if (innerType.isNull())
1008 return {};
1009
1010 if (innerType.getAsOpaquePtr() == T->getInnerType().getAsOpaquePtr())
1011 return QualType(T, 0);
1012
1013 return Ctx.getParenType(innerType);
1014 }
1015
1016 SUGARED_TYPE_CLASS(Typedef)
1017 SUGARED_TYPE_CLASS(ObjCTypeParam)
1018 SUGARED_TYPE_CLASS(MacroQualified)
1019
1020 QualType VisitAdjustedType(const AdjustedType *T) {
1021 QualType originalType = recurse(T->getOriginalType());
1022 if (originalType.isNull())
1023 return {};
1024
1025 QualType adjustedType = recurse(T->getAdjustedType());
1026 if (adjustedType.isNull())
1027 return {};
1028
1029 if (originalType.getAsOpaquePtr()
1030 == T->getOriginalType().getAsOpaquePtr() &&
1031 adjustedType.getAsOpaquePtr() == T->getAdjustedType().getAsOpaquePtr())
1032 return QualType(T, 0);
1033
1034 return Ctx.getAdjustedType(originalType, adjustedType);
1035 }

1037 QualType VisitDecayedType(const DecayedType *T) {
1038 QualType originalType = recurse(T->getOriginalType());
1039 if (originalType.isNull())
1040 return {};
1041
1042 if (originalType.getAsOpaquePtr()
1043 == T->getOriginalType().getAsOpaquePtr())
1044 return QualType(T, 0);
1045
1046 return Ctx.getDecayedType(originalType);
1047 }

1049 SUGARED_TYPE_CLASS(TypeOfExpr)
1050 SUGARED_TYPE_CLASS(TypeOf)
1051 SUGARED_TYPE_CLASS(Decltype)
1052 SUGARED_TYPE_CLASS(UnaryTransform)
1053 TRIVIAL_TYPE_CLASS(Record)
1054 TRIVIAL_TYPE_CLASS(Enum)
1055
1056 // FIXME: Non-trivial to implement, but important for C++
1057 SUGARED_TYPE_CLASS(Elaborated)
1058
1059 QualType VisitAttributedType(const AttributedType *T) {
1060 QualType modifiedType = recurse(T->getModifiedType());
1061 if (modifiedType.isNull())
1062 return {};
1063
1064 QualType equivalentType = recurse(T->getEquivalentType());
1065 if (equivalentType.isNull())
1066 return {};
1067
1068 if (modifiedType.getAsOpaquePtr()
1069 == T->getModifiedType().getAsOpaquePtr() &&
1070 equivalentType.getAsOpaquePtr()
1071 == T->getEquivalentType().getAsOpaquePtr())
1072 return QualType(T, 0);
1073
1074 return Ctx.getAttributedType(T->getAttrKind(), modifiedType,
1075 equivalentType);
1076 }
1077
1078 QualType VisitSubstTemplateTypeParmType(const SubstTemplateTypeParmType *T) {
1079 QualType replacementType = recurse(T->getReplacementType());
1080 if (replacementType.isNull())
1081 return {};
1082
1083 if (replacementType.getAsOpaquePtr()
1084 == T->getReplacementType().getAsOpaquePtr())
1085 return QualType(T, 0);
1086
1087 return Ctx.getSubstTemplateTypeParmType(T->getReplacedParameter(),
1088 replacementType);
1089 }
1090
1091 // FIXME: Non-trivial to implement, but important for C++
1092 SUGARED_TYPE_CLASS(TemplateSpecialization)
1093
1094 QualType VisitAutoType(const AutoType *T) {
1095 if (!T->isDeduced())
1096 return QualType(T, 0);
1097
1098 QualType deducedType = recurse(T->getDeducedType());
1099 if (deducedType.isNull())
1100 return {};
1101
1102 if (deducedType.getAsOpaquePtr()
1103 == T->getDeducedType().getAsOpaquePtr())
1104 return QualType(T, 0);
1105
1106 return Ctx.getAutoType(deducedType, T->getKeyword(),
1107 T->isDependentType());
1108 }
1109
1110 // FIXME: Non-trivial to implement, but important for C++
1111 SUGARED_TYPE_CLASS(PackExpansion)
1112
1113 QualType VisitObjCObjectType(const ObjCObjectType *T) {
1114 QualType baseType = recurse(T->getBaseType());
1115 if (baseType.isNull())
1116 return {};
1117
1118 // Transform type arguments.
1119 bool typeArgChanged = false;
1120 SmallVector<QualType, 4> typeArgs;
1121 for (auto typeArg : T->getTypeArgsAsWritten()) {
1122 QualType newTypeArg = recurse(typeArg);
1123 if (newTypeArg.isNull())
1124 return {};
1125
1126 if (newTypeArg.getAsOpaquePtr() != typeArg.getAsOpaquePtr())
1127 typeArgChanged = true;
1128
1129 typeArgs.push_back(newTypeArg);
1130 }
1131
1132 if (baseType.getAsOpaquePtr() == T->getBaseType().getAsOpaquePtr() &&
1133 !typeArgChanged)
1134 return QualType(T, 0);
1135
1136 return Ctx.getObjCObjectType(baseType, typeArgs,
1137 llvm::makeArrayRef(T->qual_begin(),
1138 T->getNumProtocols()),
1139 T->isKindOfTypeAsWritten());
1140 }
1141
1142 TRIVIAL_TYPE_CLASS(ObjCInterface)
1143
1144 QualType VisitObjCObjectPointerType(const ObjCObjectPointerType *T) {
1145 QualType pointeeType = recurse(T->getPointeeType());
1146 if (pointeeType.isNull())
1147 return {};
1148
1149 if (pointeeType.getAsOpaquePtr()
1150 == T->getPointeeType().getAsOpaquePtr())
1151 return QualType(T, 0);
1152
1153 return Ctx.getObjCObjectPointerType(pointeeType);
1154 }

1157 QualType valueType = recurse(T->getValueType());
1158 if (valueType.isNull())
1159 return {};
1160
1161 if (valueType.getAsOpaquePtr()
1162 == T->getValueType().getAsOpaquePtr())
1163 return QualType(T, 0);
1164
1165 return Ctx.getAtomicType(valueType);
1166 }

1168#undef TRIVIAL_TYPE_CLASS
1169#undef SUGARED_TYPE_CLASS
1170};
1171
1172struct SubstObjCTypeArgsVisitor
1173 : public SimpleTransformVisitor<SubstObjCTypeArgsVisitor> {
1174 using BaseType = SimpleTransformVisitor<SubstObjCTypeArgsVisitor>;
1175
1176 ArrayRef<QualType> TypeArgs;
1177 ObjCSubstitutionContext SubstContext;
1178
1179 SubstObjCTypeArgsVisitor(ASTContext &ctx, ArrayRef<QualType> typeArgs,
1180 ObjCSubstitutionContext context)
1181 : BaseType(ctx), TypeArgs(typeArgs), SubstContext(context) {}
1182
1183 QualType VisitObjCTypeParamType(const ObjCTypeParamType *OTPTy) {
1184 // Replace an Objective-C type parameter reference with the corresponding
1185 // type argument.
1186 ObjCTypeParamDecl *typeParam = OTPTy->getDecl();
1187 // If we have type arguments, use them.
1188 if (!TypeArgs.empty()) {
1189 QualType argType = TypeArgs[typeParam->getIndex()];
1190 if (OTPTy->qual_empty())
1191 return argType;
1192
1193 // Apply protocol lists if exists.
1194 bool hasError;
1195 SmallVector<ObjCProtocolDecl *, 8> protocolsVec;
1196 protocolsVec.append(OTPTy->qual_begin(), OTPTy->qual_end());
1197 ArrayRef<ObjCProtocolDecl *> protocolsToApply = protocolsVec;
1198 return Ctx.applyObjCProtocolQualifiers(
1199 argType, protocolsToApply, hasError, true/*allowOnPointerType*/);
1200 }
1201
1202 switch (SubstContext) {
1203 case ObjCSubstitutionContext::Ordinary:
1204 case ObjCSubstitutionContext::Parameter:
1205 case ObjCSubstitutionContext::Superclass:
1206 // Substitute the bound.
1207 return typeParam->getUnderlyingType();
1208
1209 case ObjCSubstitutionContext::Result:
1210 case ObjCSubstitutionContext::Property: {
1211 // Substitute the __kindof form of the underlying type.
1212 const auto *objPtr =
1213 typeParam->getUnderlyingType()->castAs<ObjCObjectPointerType>();
1214
1215 // __kindof types, id, and Class don't need an additional
1216 // __kindof.
1217 if (objPtr->isKindOfType() || objPtr->isObjCIdOrClassType())
1218 return typeParam->getUnderlyingType();
1219
1220 // Add __kindof.
1221 const auto *obj = objPtr->getObjectType();
1222 QualType resultTy = Ctx.getObjCObjectType(
1223 obj->getBaseType(), obj->getTypeArgsAsWritten(), obj->getProtocols(),
1224 /*isKindOf=*/true);
1225
1226 // Rebuild object pointer type.
1227 return Ctx.getObjCObjectPointerType(resultTy);
1228 }
1229 }
1230 llvm_unreachable("Unexpected ObjCSubstitutionContext!");
1231 }
1232
1233 QualType VisitFunctionType(const FunctionType *funcType) {
1234 // If we have a function type, update the substitution context
1235 // appropriately.
1236
1237 //Substitute result type.
1238 QualType returnType = funcType->getReturnType().substObjCTypeArgs(
1239 Ctx, TypeArgs, ObjCSubstitutionContext::Result);
1240 if (returnType.isNull())
1241 return {};
1242
1243 // Handle non-prototyped functions, which only substitute into the result
1244 // type.
1245 if (isa<FunctionNoProtoType>(funcType)) {
1246 // If the return type was unchanged, do nothing.
1247 if (returnType.getAsOpaquePtr() ==
1248 funcType->getReturnType().getAsOpaquePtr())
1249 return BaseType::VisitFunctionType(funcType);
1250
1251 // Otherwise, build a new type.
1252 return Ctx.getFunctionNoProtoType(returnType, funcType->getExtInfo());
1253 }
1254
1255 const auto *funcProtoType = cast<FunctionProtoType>(funcType);
1256
1257 // Transform parameter types.
1258 SmallVector<QualType, 4> paramTypes;
1259 bool paramChanged = false;
1260 for (auto paramType : funcProtoType->getParamTypes()) {
1261 QualType newParamType = paramType.substObjCTypeArgs(
1262 Ctx, TypeArgs, ObjCSubstitutionContext::Parameter);
1263 if (newParamType.isNull())
1264 return {};
1265
1266 if (newParamType.getAsOpaquePtr() != paramType.getAsOpaquePtr())
1267 paramChanged = true;
1268
1269 paramTypes.push_back(newParamType);
1270 }
1271
1272 // Transform extended info.
1273 FunctionProtoType::ExtProtoInfo info = funcProtoType->getExtProtoInfo();
1274 bool exceptionChanged = false;
1275 if (info.ExceptionSpec.Type == EST_Dynamic) {
1276 SmallVector<QualType, 4> exceptionTypes;
1277 for (auto exceptionType : info.ExceptionSpec.Exceptions) {
1278 QualType newExceptionType = exceptionType.substObjCTypeArgs(
1279 Ctx, TypeArgs, ObjCSubstitutionContext::Ordinary);
1280 if (newExceptionType.isNull())
1281 return {};
1282
1283 if (newExceptionType.getAsOpaquePtr() != exceptionType.getAsOpaquePtr())
1284 exceptionChanged = true;
1285
1286 exceptionTypes.push_back(newExceptionType);
1287 }
1288
1289 if (exceptionChanged) {
1290 info.ExceptionSpec.Exceptions =
1291 llvm::makeArrayRef(exceptionTypes).copy(Ctx);
1292 }
1293 }
1294
1295 if (returnType.getAsOpaquePtr() ==
1296 funcProtoType->getReturnType().getAsOpaquePtr() &&
1297 !paramChanged && !exceptionChanged)
1298 return BaseType::VisitFunctionType(funcType);
1299
1300 return Ctx.getFunctionType(returnType, paramTypes, info);
1301 }
1302
1303 QualType VisitObjCObjectType(const ObjCObjectType *objcObjectType) {
1304 // Substitute into the type arguments of a specialized Objective-C object
1305 // type.
1306 if (objcObjectType->isSpecializedAsWritten()) {
1307 SmallVector<QualType, 4> newTypeArgs;
1308 bool anyChanged = false;
1309 for (auto typeArg : objcObjectType->getTypeArgsAsWritten()) {
1310 QualType newTypeArg = typeArg.substObjCTypeArgs(
1311 Ctx, TypeArgs, ObjCSubstitutionContext::Ordinary);
1312 if (newTypeArg.isNull())
1313 return {};
1314
1315 if (newTypeArg.getAsOpaquePtr() != typeArg.getAsOpaquePtr()) {
1316 // If we're substituting based on an unspecialized context type,
1317 // produce an unspecialized type.
1318 ArrayRef<ObjCProtocolDecl *> protocols(
1319 objcObjectType->qual_begin(), objcObjectType->getNumProtocols());
1320 if (TypeArgs.empty() &&
1321 SubstContext != ObjCSubstitutionContext::Superclass) {
1322 return Ctx.getObjCObjectType(
1323 objcObjectType->getBaseType(), {}, protocols,
1324 objcObjectType->isKindOfTypeAsWritten());
1325 }
1326
1327 anyChanged = true;
1328 }
1329
1330 newTypeArgs.push_back(newTypeArg);
1331 }
1332
1333 if (anyChanged) {
1334 ArrayRef<ObjCProtocolDecl *> protocols(
1335 objcObjectType->qual_begin(), objcObjectType->getNumProtocols());
1336 return Ctx.getObjCObjectType(objcObjectType->getBaseType(), newTypeArgs,
1337 protocols,
1338 objcObjectType->isKindOfTypeAsWritten());
1339 }
1340 }
1341
1342 return BaseType::VisitObjCObjectType(objcObjectType);
1343 }
1344
1345 QualType VisitAttributedType(const AttributedType *attrType) {
1346 QualType newType = BaseType::VisitAttributedType(attrType);
1347 if (newType.isNull())
1348 return {};
1349
1350 const auto *newAttrType = dyn_cast<AttributedType>(newType.getTypePtr());
1351 if (!newAttrType || newAttrType->getAttrKind() != attr::ObjCKindOf)
1352 return newType;
1353
1354 // Find out if it's an Objective-C object or object pointer type;
1355 QualType newEquivType = newAttrType->getEquivalentType();
1356 const ObjCObjectPointerType *ptrType =
1357 newEquivType->getAs<ObjCObjectPointerType>();
1358 const ObjCObjectType *objType = ptrType
1359 ? ptrType->getObjectType()
1360 : newEquivType->getAs<ObjCObjectType>();
1361 if (!objType)
1362 return newType;
1363
1364 // Rebuild the "equivalent" type, which pushes __kindof down into
1365 // the object type.
1366 newEquivType = Ctx.getObjCObjectType(
1367 objType->getBaseType(), objType->getTypeArgsAsWritten(),
1368 objType->getProtocols(),
1369 // There is no need to apply kindof on an unqualified id type.
1370 /*isKindOf=*/objType->isObjCUnqualifiedId() ? false : true);
1371
1372 // If we started with an object pointer type, rebuild it.
1373 if (ptrType)
1374 newEquivType = Ctx.getObjCObjectPointerType(newEquivType);
1375
1376 // Rebuild the attributed type.
1377 return Ctx.getAttributedType(newAttrType->getAttrKind(),
1378 newAttrType->getModifiedType(), newEquivType);
1379 }
1380};
1381
1382struct StripObjCKindOfTypeVisitor
1383 : public SimpleTransformVisitor<StripObjCKindOfTypeVisitor> {
1384 using BaseType = SimpleTransformVisitor<StripObjCKindOfTypeVisitor>;
1385
1386 explicit StripObjCKindOfTypeVisitor(ASTContext &ctx) : BaseType(ctx) {}
1387
1388 QualType VisitObjCObjectType(const ObjCObjectType *objType) {
1389 if (!objType->isKindOfType())
1390 return BaseType::VisitObjCObjectType(objType);
1391
1392 QualType baseType = objType->getBaseType().stripObjCKindOfType(Ctx);
1393 return Ctx.getObjCObjectType(baseType, objType->getTypeArgsAsWritten(),
1394 objType->getProtocols(),
1395 /*isKindOf=*/false);
1396 }
1397};

1431
1432Optional<ArrayRef<QualType>> Type::getObjCSubstitutions(
1433 const DeclContext *dc) const {
1434 // Look through method scopes.
1435 if (const auto method = dyn_cast<ObjCMethodDecl>(dc))
1436 dc = method->getDeclContext();
1437
1438 // Find the class or category in which the type we're substituting
1439 // was declared.
1440 const auto *dcClassDecl = dyn_cast<ObjCInterfaceDecl>(dc);
1441 const ObjCCategoryDecl *dcCategoryDecl = nullptr;
1442 ObjCTypeParamList *dcTypeParams = nullptr;
1443 if (dcClassDecl) {
1444 // If the class does not have any type parameters, there's no
1445 // substitution to do.
1446 dcTypeParams = dcClassDecl->getTypeParamList();
1447 if (!dcTypeParams)
1448 return None;
1449 } else {
1450 // If we are in neither a class nor a category, there's no
1451 // substitution to perform.
1452 dcCategoryDecl = dyn_cast<ObjCCategoryDecl>(dc);
1453 if (!dcCategoryDecl)
1454 return None;
1455
1456 // If the category does not have any type parameters, there's no
1457 // substitution to do.
1458 dcTypeParams = dcCategoryDecl->getTypeParamList();
1459 if (!dcTypeParams)
1460 return None;
1461
1462 dcClassDecl = dcCategoryDecl->getClassInterface();
1463 if (!dcClassDecl)
1464 return None;
1465 }
1466 assert(dcTypeParams && "No substitutions to perform");
1467 assert(dcClassDecl && "No class context");
1468
1469 // Find the underlying object type.
1470 const ObjCObjectType *objectType;
1471 if (const auto *objectPointerType = getAs<ObjCObjectPointerType>()) {
1472 objectType = objectPointerType->getObjectType();
1473 } else if (getAs<BlockPointerType>()) {
1474 ASTContext &ctx = dc->getParentASTContext();
1475 objectType = ctx.getObjCObjectType(ctx.ObjCBuiltinIdTy, {}, {})
1476 ->castAs<ObjCObjectType>();
1477 } else {
1478 objectType = getAs<ObjCObjectType>();
1479 }
1480
1481 /// Extract the class from the receiver object type.
1482 ObjCInterfaceDecl *curClassDecl = objectType ? objectType->getInterface()
1483 : nullptr;
1484 if (!curClassDecl) {
1485 // If we don't have a context type (e.g., this is "id" or some
1486 // variant thereof), substitute the bounds.
1487 return llvm::ArrayRef<QualType>();
1488 }
1489
1490 // Follow the superclass chain until we've mapped the receiver type
1491 // to the same class as the context.
1492 while (curClassDecl != dcClassDecl) {
1493 // Map to the superclass type.
1494 QualType superType = objectType->getSuperClassType();
1495 if (superType.isNull()) {
1496 objectType = nullptr;
1497 break;
1498 }
1499
1500 objectType = superType->castAs<ObjCObjectType>();
1501 curClassDecl = objectType->getInterface();
1502 }
1503
1504 // If we don't have a receiver type, or the receiver type does not
1505 // have type arguments, substitute in the defaults.
1506 if (!objectType || objectType->isUnspecialized()) {
1507 return llvm::ArrayRef<QualType>();
1508 }
1509
1510 // The receiver type has the type arguments we want.
1511 return objectType->getTypeArgs();
1512}

1514bool Type::acceptsObjCTypeParams() const {
1515 if (auto *IfaceT = getAsObjCInterfaceType()) {
1516 if (auto *ID = IfaceT->getInterface()) {
1517 if (ID->getTypeParamList())
1518 return true;
1519 }
1520 }
1521
1522 return false;
1523}
1524
1525void ObjCObjectType::computeSuperClassTypeSlow() const {
1526 // Retrieve the class declaration for this type. If there isn't one
1527 // (e.g., this is some variant of "id" or "Class"), then there is no
1528 // superclass type.
1529 ObjCInterfaceDecl *classDecl = getInterface();
1530 if (!classDecl) {
1531 CachedSuperClassType.setInt(true);
1532 return;
1533 }
1534
1535 // Extract the superclass type.
1536 const ObjCObjectType *superClassObjTy = classDecl->getSuperClassType();
1537 if (!superClassObjTy) {
1538 CachedSuperClassType.setInt(true);
1539 return;
1540 }
1541
1542 ObjCInterfaceDecl *superClassDecl = superClassObjTy->getInterface();
1543 if (!superClassDecl) {
1544 CachedSuperClassType.setInt(true);
1545 return;
1546 }
1547
1548 // If the superclass doesn't have type parameters, then there is no
1549 // substitution to perform.
1550 QualType superClassType(superClassObjTy, 0);
1551 ObjCTypeParamList *superClassTypeParams = superClassDecl->getTypeParamList();
1552 if (!superClassTypeParams) {
1553 CachedSuperClassType.setPointerAndInt(
1554 superClassType->castAs<ObjCObjectType>(), true);
1555 return;
1556 }
1557
1558 // If the superclass reference is unspecialized, return it.
1559 if (superClassObjTy->isUnspecialized()) {
1560 CachedSuperClassType.setPointerAndInt(superClassObjTy, true);
1561 return;
1562 }
1563
1564 // If the subclass is not parameterized, there aren't any type
1565 // parameters in the superclass reference to substitute.
1566 ObjCTypeParamList *typeParams = classDecl->getTypeParamList();
1567 if (!typeParams) {
1568 CachedSuperClassType.setPointerAndInt(
1569 superClassType->castAs<ObjCObjectType>(), true);
1570 return;
1571 }
1572
1573 // If the subclass type isn't specialized, return the unspecialized
1574 // superclass.
1575 if (isUnspecialized()) {
1576 QualType unspecializedSuper
1577 = classDecl->getASTContext().getObjCInterfaceType(
1578 superClassObjTy->getInterface());
1579 CachedSuperClassType.setPointerAndInt(
1580 unspecializedSuper->castAs<ObjCObjectType>(),
1581 true);
1582 return;
1583 }
1584
1585 // Substitute the provided type arguments into the superclass type.
1586 ArrayRef<QualType> typeArgs = getTypeArgs();
1587 assert(typeArgs.size() == typeParams->size());
1588 CachedSuperClassType.setPointerAndInt(
1589 superClassType.substObjCTypeArgs(classDecl->getASTContext(), typeArgs,
1590 ObjCSubstitutionContext::Superclass)
1591 ->castAs<ObjCObjectType>(),
1592 true);
1593}

1813/// Determine whether this type is an integral type.
1814///
1815/// This routine determines whether the given type is an integral type per
1816/// C++ [basic.fundamental]p7. Although the C standard does not define the
1817/// term "integral type", it has a similar term "integer type", and in C++
1818/// the two terms are equivalent. However, C's "integer type" includes
1819/// enumeration types, while C++'s "integer type" does not. The \c ASTContext
1820/// parameter is used to determine whether we should be following the C or
1821/// C++ rules when determining whether this type is an integral/integer type.
1822///
1823/// For cases where C permits "an integer type" and C++ permits "an integral
1824/// type", use this routine.
1825///
1826/// For cases where C permits "an integer type" and C++ permits "an integral
1827/// or enumeration type", use \c isIntegralOrEnumerationType() instead.
1828///
1829/// \param Ctx The context in which this type occurs.
1830///
1831/// \returns true if the type is considered an integral type, false otherwise.
1832bool Type::isIntegralType(const ASTContext &Ctx) const {
1833 if (const auto *BT = dyn_cast<BuiltinType>(CanonicalType))
1834 return BT->getKind() >= BuiltinType::Bool &&
1835 BT->getKind() <= BuiltinType::Int128;
1836
1837 // Complete enum types are integral in C.
1838 if (!Ctx.getLangOpts().CPlusPlus)
1839 if (const auto *ET = dyn_cast<EnumType>(CanonicalType))
1840 return ET->getDecl()->isComplete();
1841
1842 return false;
1843}
1844
1845bool Type::isIntegralOrUnscopedEnumerationType() const {
1846 if (const auto *BT = dyn_cast<BuiltinType>(CanonicalType))
1847 return BT->getKind() >= BuiltinType::Bool &&
1848 BT->getKind() <= BuiltinType::Int128;
1849
1850 // Check for a complete enum type; incomplete enum types are not properly an
1851 // enumeration type in the sense required here.
1852 // C++0x: However, if the underlying type of the enum is fixed, it is
1853 // considered complete.
1854 if (const auto *ET = dyn_cast<EnumType>(CanonicalType))
1855 return ET->getDecl()->isComplete() && !ET->getDecl()->isScoped();
1856
1857 return false;
1858}

1894/// Determine whether this type is any of the built-in character
1895/// types.
1896bool Type::isAnyCharacterType() const {

1901 case BuiltinType::Char_U:
1902 case BuiltinType::UChar:
1903 case BuiltinType::WChar_U:
1904 case BuiltinType::Char8:
1905 case BuiltinType::Char16:
1906 case BuiltinType::Char32:
1907 case BuiltinType::Char_S:
1908 case BuiltinType::SChar:
1909 case BuiltinType::WChar_S:
1910 return true;
1911 }

1914/// isSignedIntegerType - Return true if this is an integer type that is
1915/// signed, according to C99 6.2.5p4 [char, signed char, short, int, long..],
1916/// an enum decl which has a signed representation
1917bool Type::isSignedIntegerType() const {
1918 if (const auto *BT = dyn_cast<BuiltinType>(CanonicalType)) {
1919 return BT->getKind() >= BuiltinType::Char_S &&
1920 BT->getKind() <= BuiltinType::Int128;
1921 }
1922
1923 if (const EnumType *ET = dyn_cast<EnumType>(CanonicalType)) {
1924 // Incomplete enum types are not treated as integer types.
1925 // FIXME: In C++, enum types are never integer types.
1926 if (ET->getDecl()->isComplete() && !ET->getDecl()->isScoped())
1927 return ET->getDecl()->getIntegerType()->isSignedIntegerType();
1928 }
1929
1930 return false;
1931}

2025bool Type::isArithmeticType() const {
2026 if (const auto *BT = dyn_cast<BuiltinType>(CanonicalType))
2027 return BT->getKind() >= BuiltinType::Bool &&
2028 BT->getKind() <= BuiltinType::Float128;
2029 if (const auto *ET = dyn_cast<EnumType>(CanonicalType))
2030 // GCC allows forward declaration of enum types (forbid by C99 6.7.2.3p2).
2031 // If a body isn't seen by the time we get here, return false.
2032 //
2033 // C++0x: Enumerations are not arithmetic types. For now, just return
2034 // false for scoped enumerations since that will disable any
2035 // unwanted implicit conversions.
2036 return !ET->getDecl()->isScoped() && ET->getDecl()->isComplete();
2037 return isa<ComplexType>(CanonicalType);
2038}
2039
2040Type::ScalarTypeKind Type::getScalarTypeKind() const {
2041 assert(isScalarType());
2042
2043 const Type *T = CanonicalType.getTypePtr();
2044 if (const auto *BT = dyn_cast<BuiltinType>(T)) {
2045 if (BT->getKind() == BuiltinType::Bool) return STK_Bool;
2046 if (BT->getKind() == BuiltinType::NullPtr) return STK_CPointer;
2047 if (BT->isInteger()) return STK_Integral;
2048 if (BT->isFloatingPoint()) return STK_Floating;
2049 if (BT->isFixedPointType()) return STK_FixedPoint;
2050 llvm_unreachable("unknown scalar builtin type");
2051 } else if (isa<PointerType>(T)) {
2052 return STK_CPointer;
2053 } else if (isa<BlockPointerType>(T)) {
2054 return STK_BlockPointer;
2055 } else if (isa<ObjCObjectPointerType>(T)) {
2056 return STK_ObjCObjectPointer;
2057 } else if (isa<MemberPointerType>(T)) {
2058 return STK_MemberPointer;
2059 } else if (isa<EnumType>(T)) {
2060 assert(cast<EnumType>(T)->getDecl()->isComplete());
2061 return STK_Integral;
2062 } else if (const auto *CT = dyn_cast<ComplexType>(T)) {
2063 if (CT->getElementType()->isRealFloatingType())
2064 return STK_FloatingComplex;
2065 return STK_IntegralComplex;
2066 }
2067
2068 llvm_unreachable("unknown scalar type");
2069}

2071/// Determines whether the type is a C++ aggregate type or C
2072/// aggregate or union type.
2073///
2074/// An aggregate type is an array or a class type (struct, union, or
2075/// class) that has no user-declared constructors, no private or
2076/// protected non-static data members, no base classes, and no virtual
2077/// functions (C++ [dcl.init.aggr]p1). The notion of an aggregate type
2078/// subsumes the notion of C aggregates (C99 6.2.5p21) because it also
2079/// includes union types.
2080bool Type::isAggregateType() const {
2081 if (const auto *Record = dyn_cast<RecordType>(CanonicalType)) {
2082 if (const auto *ClassDecl = dyn_cast<CXXRecordDecl>(Record->getDecl()))
2083 return ClassDecl->isAggregate();
2084
2085 return true;
2086 }
2087
2088 return isa<ArrayType>(CanonicalType);
2089}

2091/// isConstantSizeType - Return true if this is not a variable sized type,
2092/// according to the rules of C99 6.7.5p3. It is not legal to call this on
2093/// incomplete types or dependent types.
2094bool Type::isConstantSizeType() const {
2095 assert(!isIncompleteType() && "This doesn't make sense for incomplete types");
2096 assert(!isDependentType() && "This doesn't make sense for dependent types");
2097 // The VAT must have a size, as it is known to be complete.
2098 return !isa<VariableArrayType>(CanonicalType);
2099}
2100
2101/// isIncompleteType - Return true if this is an incomplete type (C99 6.2.5p1)
2102/// - a type that can describe objects, but which lacks information needed to
2103/// determine its size.
2104bool Type::isIncompleteType(NamedDecl **Def) const {
2105 if (Def)
2106 *Def = nullptr;
2107
2108 switch (CanonicalType->getTypeClass()) {
2109 default: return false;
2110 case Builtin:
2111 // Void is the only incomplete builtin type. Per C99 6.2.5p19, it can never
2112 // be completed.
2113 return isVoidType();
2114 case Enum: {
2115 EnumDecl *EnumD = cast<EnumType>(CanonicalType)->getDecl();
2116 if (Def)
2117 *Def = EnumD;
2118 return !EnumD->isComplete();
2119 }
2120 case Record: {
2121 // A tagged type (struct/union/enum/class) is incomplete if the decl is a
2122 // forward declaration, but not a full definition (C99 6.2.5p22).
2123 RecordDecl *Rec = cast<RecordType>(CanonicalType)->getDecl();
2124 if (Def)
2125 *Def = Rec;
2126 return !Rec->isCompleteDefinition();
2127 }
2128 case ConstantArray:
2129 // An array is incomplete if its element type is incomplete
2130 // (C++ [dcl.array]p1).
2131 // We don't handle variable arrays (they're not allowed in C++) or
2132 // dependent-sized arrays (dependent types are never treated as incomplete).
2133 return cast<ArrayType>(CanonicalType)->getElementType()
2134 ->isIncompleteType(Def);
2135 case IncompleteArray:
2136 // An array of unknown size is an incomplete type (C99 6.2.5p22).
2137 return true;
2138 case MemberPointer: {
2139 // Member pointers in the MS ABI have special behavior in
2140 // RequireCompleteType: they attach a MSInheritanceAttr to the CXXRecordDecl
2141 // to indicate which inheritance model to use.
2142 auto *MPTy = cast<MemberPointerType>(CanonicalType);
2143 const Type *ClassTy = MPTy->getClass();
2144 // Member pointers with dependent class types don't get special treatment.
2145 if (ClassTy->isDependentType())
2146 return false;
2147 const CXXRecordDecl *RD = ClassTy->getAsCXXRecordDecl();
2148 ASTContext &Context = RD->getASTContext();
2149 // Member pointers not in the MS ABI don't get special treatment.
2150 if (!Context.getTargetInfo().getCXXABI().isMicrosoft())
2151 return false;
2152 // The inheritance attribute might only be present on the most recent
2153 // CXXRecordDecl, use that one.
2154 RD = RD->getMostRecentNonInjectedDecl();
2155 // Nothing interesting to do if the inheritance attribute is already set.
2156 if (RD->hasAttr<MSInheritanceAttr>())
2157 return false;
2158 return true;
2159 }
2160 case ObjCObject:
2161 return cast<ObjCObjectType>(CanonicalType)->getBaseType()
2162 ->isIncompleteType(Def);
2163 case ObjCInterface: {
2164 // ObjC interfaces are incomplete if they are @class, not @interface.
2165 ObjCInterfaceDecl *Interface
2166 = cast<ObjCInterfaceType>(CanonicalType)->getDecl();
2167 if (Def)
2168 *Def = Interface;
2169 return !Interface->hasDefinition();
2170 }
2171 }
2172}

2174bool QualType::isPODType(const ASTContext &Context) const {
2175 // C++11 has a more relaxed definition of POD.
2176 if (Context.getLangOpts().CPlusPlus11)
2177 return isCXX11PODType(Context);
2178
2179 return isCXX98PODType(Context);
2180}

2182bool QualType::isCXX98PODType(const ASTContext &Context) const {
2183 // The compiler shouldn't query this for incomplete types, but the user might.
2184 // We return false for that case. Except for incomplete arrays of PODs, which
2185 // are PODs according to the standard.
2186 if (isNull())
2187 return false;
2188
2189 if ((*this)->isIncompleteArrayType())
2190 return Context.getBaseElementType(*this).isCXX98PODType(Context);
2191
2192 if ((*this)->isIncompleteType())
2193 return false;
2194
2195 if (hasNonTrivialObjCLifetime())
2196 return false;
2197
2198 QualType CanonicalType = getTypePtr()->CanonicalType;
2199 switch (CanonicalType->getTypeClass()) {
2200 // Everything not explicitly mentioned is not POD.
2201 default: return false;
2202 case Type::VariableArray:
2203 case Type::ConstantArray:
2204 // IncompleteArray is handled above.
2205 return Context.getBaseElementType(*this).isCXX98PODType(Context);
2206
2207 case Type::ObjCObjectPointer:
2208 case Type::BlockPointer:
2209 case Type::Builtin:
2210 case Type::Complex:
2211 case Type::Pointer:
2212 case Type::MemberPointer:
2213 case Type::Vector:
2214 case Type::ExtVector:
2215 return true;
2216
2217 case Type::Enum:
2218 return true;
2219
2220 case Type::Record:
2221 if (const auto *ClassDecl =
2222 dyn_cast<CXXRecordDecl>(cast<RecordType>(CanonicalType)->getDecl()))
2223 return ClassDecl->isPOD();
2224
2225 // C struct/union is POD.
2226 return true;
2227 }
2228}
2229
2230bool QualType::isTrivialType(const ASTContext &Context) const {
2231 // The compiler shouldn't query this for incomplete types, but the user might.
2232 // We return false for that case. Except for incomplete arrays of PODs, which
2233 // are PODs according to the standard.
2234 if (isNull())
2235 return false;
2236
2237 if ((*this)->isArrayType())
2238 return Context.getBaseElementType(*this).isTrivialType(Context);
2239
2240 // Return false for incomplete types after skipping any incomplete array
2241 // types which are expressly allowed by the standard and thus our API.
2242 if ((*this)->isIncompleteType())
2243 return false;
2244
2245 if (hasNonTrivialObjCLifetime())
2246 return false;
2247
2248 QualType CanonicalType = getTypePtr()->CanonicalType;
2249 if (CanonicalType->isDependentType())
2250 return false;
2251
2252 // C++0x [basic.types]p9:
2253 // Scalar types, trivial class types, arrays of such types, and
2254 // cv-qualified versions of these types are collectively called trivial
2255 // types.
2256
2257 // As an extension, Clang treats vector types as Scalar types.
2258 if (CanonicalType->isScalarType() || CanonicalType->isVectorType())
2259 return true;
2260 if (const auto *RT = CanonicalType->getAs<RecordType>()) {
2261 if (const auto *ClassDecl = dyn_cast<CXXRecordDecl>(RT->getDecl())) {
2262 // C++11 [class]p6:
2263 // A trivial class is a class that has a default constructor,
2264 // has no non-trivial default constructors, and is trivially
2265 // copyable.
2266 return ClassDecl->hasDefaultConstructor() &&
2267 !ClassDecl->hasNonTrivialDefaultConstructor() &&
2268 ClassDecl->isTriviallyCopyable();
2269 }
2270
2271 return true;
2272 }
2273
2274 // No other types can match.
2275 return false;
2276}
2277
2278bool QualType::isTriviallyCopyableType(const ASTContext &Context) const {
2279 if ((*this)->isArrayType())
2280 return Context.getBaseElementType(*this).isTriviallyCopyableType(Context);
2281
2282 if (hasNonTrivialObjCLifetime())
2283 return false;
2284
2285 // C++11 [basic.types]p9 - See Core 2094
2286 // Scalar types, trivially copyable class types, arrays of such types, and
2287 // cv-qualified versions of these types are collectively
2288 // called trivially copyable types.
2289
2290 QualType CanonicalType = getCanonicalType();
2291 if (CanonicalType->isDependentType())
2292 return false;
2293
2294 // Return false for incomplete types after skipping any incomplete array types
2295 // which are expressly allowed by the standard and thus our API.
2296 if (CanonicalType->isIncompleteType())
2297 return false;
2298
2299 // As an extension, Clang treats vector types as Scalar types.
2300 if (CanonicalType->isScalarType() || CanonicalType->isVectorType())
2301 return true;
2302
2303 if (const auto *RT = CanonicalType->getAs<RecordType>()) {
2304 if (const auto *ClassDecl = dyn_cast<CXXRecordDecl>(RT->getDecl())) {
2305 if (!ClassDecl->isTriviallyCopyable()) return false;
2306 }
2307
2308 return true;
2309 }
2310
2311 // No other types can match.
2312 return false;
2313}

2317 Context.getLangOpts().ObjCWeak &&
2318 getObjCLifetime() != Qualifiers::OCL_Weak;

2321namespace {
2322// Helper class that determines whether this is a type that is non-trivial to
2323// primitive copy or move, or is a struct type that has a field of such type.
2324template <bool IsMove>
2325struct IsNonTrivialCopyMoveVisitor
2326 : CopiedTypeVisitor<IsNonTrivialCopyMoveVisitor<IsMove>, IsMove, bool> {
2327 using Super =
2328 CopiedTypeVisitor<IsNonTrivialCopyMoveVisitor<IsMove>, IsMove, bool>;
2329 IsNonTrivialCopyMoveVisitor(const ASTContext &C) : Ctx(C) {}
2330 void preVisit(QualType::PrimitiveCopyKind PCK, QualType QT) {}
2331
2332 bool visitWithKind(QualType::PrimitiveCopyKind PCK, QualType QT) {
2333 if (const auto *AT = this->Ctx.getAsArrayType(QT))
2334 return this->asDerived().visit(Ctx.getBaseElementType(AT));
2335 return Super::visitWithKind(PCK, QT);
2336 }
2337
2338 bool visitARCStrong(QualType QT) { return true; }
2339 bool visitARCWeak(QualType QT) { return true; }
2340 bool visitTrivial(QualType QT) { return false; }
2341 // Volatile fields are considered trivial.
2342 bool visitVolatileTrivial(QualType QT) { return false; }
2343
2344 bool visitStruct(QualType QT) {
2345 const RecordDecl *RD = QT->castAs<RecordType>()->getDecl();
2346 // We don't want to apply the C restriction in C++ because C++
2347 // (1) can apply the restriction at a finer grain by banning copying or
2348 // destroying the union, and
2349 // (2) allows users to override these restrictions by declaring explicit
2350 // constructors/etc, which we're not proposing to add to C.
2351 if (isa<CXXRecordDecl>(RD))
2352 return false;
2353 for (const FieldDecl *FD : RD->fields())
2354 if (this->asDerived().visit(FD->getType()))
2355 return true;
2356 return false;
2357 }
2358
2359 const ASTContext &Ctx;
2360};
2361
2362} // namespace

2364bool QualType::isNonTrivialPrimitiveCType(const ASTContext &Ctx) const {
2365 if (isNonTrivialToPrimitiveDefaultInitialize())
2366 return true;
2367 DestructionKind DK = isDestructedType();
2368 if (DK != DK_none && DK != DK_cxx_destructor)
2369 return true;
2370 if (IsNonTrivialCopyMoveVisitor<false>(Ctx).visit(*this))
2371 return true;
2372 if (IsNonTrivialCopyMoveVisitor<true>(Ctx).visit(*this))
2373 return true;
2374 return false;
2375}

2416bool Type::isLiteralType(const ASTContext &Ctx) const {
2417 if (isDependentType())
2418 return false;
2419
2420 // C++1y [basic.types]p10:
2421 // A type is a literal type if it is:
2422 // -- cv void; or
2423 if (Ctx.getLangOpts().CPlusPlus14 && isVoidType())
2424 return true;
2425
2426 // C++11 [basic.types]p10:
2427 // A type is a literal type if it is:
2428 // [...]
2429 // -- an array of literal type other than an array of runtime bound; or
2430 if (isVariableArrayType())
2431 return false;
2432 const Type *BaseTy = getBaseElementTypeUnsafe();
2433 assert(BaseTy && "NULL element type");
2434
2435 // Return false for incomplete types after skipping any incomplete array
2436 // types; those are expressly allowed by the standard and thus our API.
2437 if (BaseTy->isIncompleteType())
2438 return false;
2439
2440 // C++11 [basic.types]p10:
2441 // A type is a literal type if it is:
2442 // -- a scalar type; or
2443 // As an extension, Clang treats vector types and complex types as
2444 // literal types.
2445 if (BaseTy->isScalarType() || BaseTy->isVectorType() ||
2446 BaseTy->isAnyComplexType())
2447 return true;
2448 // -- a reference type; or
2449 if (BaseTy->isReferenceType())
2450 return true;
2451 // -- a class type that has all of the following properties:
2452 if (const auto *RT = BaseTy->getAs<RecordType>()) {
2453 // -- a trivial destructor,
2454 // -- every constructor call and full-expression in the
2455 // brace-or-equal-initializers for non-static data members (if any)
2456 // is a constant expression,
2457 // -- it is an aggregate type or has at least one constexpr
2458 // constructor or constructor template that is not a copy or move
2459 // constructor, and
2460 // -- all non-static data members and base classes of literal types
2461 //
2462 // We resolve DR1361 by ignoring the second bullet.
2463 if (const auto *ClassDecl = dyn_cast<CXXRecordDecl>(RT->getDecl()))
2464 return ClassDecl->isLiteral();
2465
2466 return true;
2467 }
2468
2469 // We treat _Atomic T as a literal type if T is a literal type.
2470 if (const auto *AT = BaseTy->getAs<AtomicType>())
2471 return AT->getValueType()->isLiteralType(Ctx);
2472
2473 // If this type hasn't been deduced yet, then conservatively assume that
2474 // it'll work out to be a literal type.
2475 if (isa<AutoType>(BaseTy->getCanonicalTypeInternal()))
2476 return true;
2477
2478 return false;
2479}

2481bool Type::isStandardLayoutType() const {
2482 if (isDependentType())
2483 return false;
2484
2485 // C++0x [basic.types]p9:
2486 // Scalar types, standard-layout class types, arrays of such types, and
2487 // cv-qualified versions of these types are collectively called
2488 // standard-layout types.
2489 const Type *BaseTy = getBaseElementTypeUnsafe();
2490 assert(BaseTy && "NULL element type");
2491
2492 // Return false for incomplete types after skipping any incomplete array
2493 // types which are expressly allowed by the standard and thus our API.
2494 if (BaseTy->isIncompleteType())
2495 return false;
2496
2497 // As an extension, Clang treats vector types as Scalar types.
2498 if (BaseTy->isScalarType() || BaseTy->isVectorType()) return true;
2499 if (const auto *RT = BaseTy->getAs<RecordType>()) {
2500 if (const auto *ClassDecl = dyn_cast<CXXRecordDecl>(RT->getDecl()))
2501 if (!ClassDecl->isStandardLayout())
2502 return false;
2503
2504 // Default to 'true' for non-C++ class types.
2505 // FIXME: This is a bit dubious, but plain C structs should trivially meet
2506 // all the requirements of standard layout classes.
2507 return true;
2508 }
2509
2510 // No other types can match.
2511 return false;
2512}

2514// This is effectively the intersection of isTrivialType and
2515// isStandardLayoutType. We implement it directly to avoid redundant
2516// conversions from a type to a CXXRecordDecl.
2517bool QualType::isCXX11PODType(const ASTContext &Context) const {
2518 const Type *ty = getTypePtr();
2519 if (ty->isDependentType())
2520 return false;
2521
2522 if (hasNonTrivialObjCLifetime())
2523 return false;
2524
2525 // C++11 [basic.types]p9:
2526 // Scalar types, POD classes, arrays of such types, and cv-qualified
2527 // versions of these types are collectively called trivial types.
2528 const Type *BaseTy = ty->getBaseElementTypeUnsafe();
2529 assert(BaseTy && "NULL element type");
2530
2531 // Return false for incomplete types after skipping any incomplete array
2532 // types which are expressly allowed by the standard and thus our API.
2533 if (BaseTy->isIncompleteType())
2534 return false;
2535
2536 // As an extension, Clang treats vector types as Scalar types.
2537 if (BaseTy->isScalarType() || BaseTy->isVectorType()) return true;
2538 if (const auto *RT = BaseTy->getAs<RecordType>()) {
2539 if (const auto *ClassDecl = dyn_cast<CXXRecordDecl>(RT->getDecl())) {
2540 // C++11 [class]p10:
2541 // A POD struct is a non-union class that is both a trivial class [...]
2542 if (!ClassDecl->isTrivial()) return false;
2543
2544 // C++11 [class]p10:
2545 // A POD struct is a non-union class that is both a trivial class and
2546 // a standard-layout class [...]
2547 if (!ClassDecl->isStandardLayout()) return false;
2548
2549 // C++11 [class]p10:
2550 // A POD struct is a non-union class that is both a trivial class and
2551 // a standard-layout class, and has no non-static data members of type
2552 // non-POD struct, non-POD union (or array of such types). [...]
2553 //
2554 // We don't directly query the recursive aspect as the requirements for
2555 // both standard-layout classes and trivial classes apply recursively
2556 // already.
2557 }
2558
2559 return true;
2560 }
2561
2562 // No other types can match.
2563 return false;
2564}

2589bool Type::isPromotableIntegerType() const {
2590 if (const auto *BT = getAs<BuiltinType>())
2591 switch (BT->getKind()) {
2592 case BuiltinType::Bool:
2593 case BuiltinType::Char_S:
2594 case BuiltinType::Char_U:
2595 case BuiltinType::SChar:
2596 case BuiltinType::UChar:
2597 case BuiltinType::Short:
2598 case BuiltinType::UShort:
2599 case BuiltinType::WChar_S:
2600 case BuiltinType::WChar_U:
2601 case BuiltinType::Char8:
2602 case BuiltinType::Char16:
2603 case BuiltinType::Char32:
2604 return true;
2605 default:
2606 return false;
2607 }
2608
2609 // Enumerated types are promotable to their compatible integer types
2610 // (C99 6.3.1.1) a.k.a. its underlying type (C++ [conv.prom]p2).
2611 if (const auto *ET = getAs<EnumType>()){
2612 if (this->isDependentType() || ET->getDecl()->getPromotionType().isNull()
2613 || ET->getDecl()->isScoped())
2614 return false;
2615
2616 return true;
2617 }
2618
2619 return false;
2620}

2988FunctionProtoType::FunctionProtoType(QualType result, ArrayRef<QualType> params,
2989 QualType canonical,
2990 const ExtProtoInfo &epi)
2991 : FunctionType(FunctionProto, result, canonical, result->isDependentType(),
2992 result->isInstantiationDependentType(),
2993 result->isVariablyModifiedType(),
2994 result->containsUnexpandedParameterPack(), epi.ExtInfo) {
2995 FunctionTypeBits.FastTypeQuals = epi.TypeQuals.getFastQualifiers();
2996 FunctionTypeBits.RefQualifier = epi.RefQualifier;
2997 FunctionTypeBits.NumParams = params.size();
2998 assert(getNumParams() == params.size() && "NumParams overflow!");
2999 FunctionTypeBits.ExceptionSpecType = epi.ExceptionSpec.Type;
3000 FunctionTypeBits.HasExtParameterInfos = !!epi.ExtParameterInfos;
3001 FunctionTypeBits.Variadic = epi.Variadic;
3002 FunctionTypeBits.HasTrailingReturn = epi.HasTrailingReturn;
3003
3004 // Fill in the extra trailing bitfields if present.
3005 if (hasExtraBitfields(epi.ExceptionSpec.Type)) {
3006 auto &ExtraBits = *getTrailingObjects<FunctionTypeExtraBitfields>();
3007 ExtraBits.NumExceptionType = epi.ExceptionSpec.Exceptions.size();
3008 }
3009
3010 // Fill in the trailing argument array.
3011 auto *argSlot = getTrailingObjects<QualType>();
3012 for (unsigned i = 0; i != getNumParams(); ++i) {
3013 if (params[i]->isDependentType())
3014 setDependent();
3015 else if (params[i]->isInstantiationDependentType())
3016 setInstantiationDependent();
3017
3018 if (params[i]->containsUnexpandedParameterPack())
3019 setContainsUnexpandedParameterPack();
3020
3021 argSlot[i] = params[i];
3022 }
3023
3024 // Fill in the exception type array if present.
3025 if (getExceptionSpecType() == EST_Dynamic) {
3026 assert(hasExtraBitfields() && "missing trailing extra bitfields!");
3027 auto *exnSlot =
3028 reinterpret_cast<QualType *>(getTrailingObjects<ExceptionType>());
3029 unsigned I = 0;
3030 for (QualType ExceptionType : epi.ExceptionSpec.Exceptions) {
3031 // Note that, before C++17, a dependent exception specification does
3032 // *not* make a type dependent; it's not even part of the C++ type
3033 // system.
3034 if (ExceptionType->isInstantiationDependentType())
3035 setInstantiationDependent();
3036
3037 if (ExceptionType->containsUnexpandedParameterPack())
3038 setContainsUnexpandedParameterPack();
3039
3040 exnSlot[I++] = ExceptionType;
3041 }
3042 }
3043 // Fill in the Expr * in the exception specification if present.
3044 else if (isComputedNoexcept(getExceptionSpecType())) {
3045 assert(epi.ExceptionSpec.NoexceptExpr && "computed noexcept with no expr");
3046 assert((getExceptionSpecType() == EST_DependentNoexcept) ==
3047 epi.ExceptionSpec.NoexceptExpr->isValueDependent());
3048
3049 // Store the noexcept expression and context.
3050 *getTrailingObjects<Expr *>() = epi.ExceptionSpec.NoexceptExpr;
3051
3052 if (epi.ExceptionSpec.NoexceptExpr->isValueDependent() ||
3053 epi.ExceptionSpec.NoexceptExpr->isInstantiationDependent())
3054 setInstantiationDependent();
3055
3056 if (epi.ExceptionSpec.NoexceptExpr->containsUnexpandedParameterPack())
3057 setContainsUnexpandedParameterPack();
3058 }
3059 // Fill in the FunctionDecl * in the exception specification if present.
3060 else if (getExceptionSpecType() == EST_Uninstantiated) {
3061 // Store the function decl from which we will resolve our
3062 // exception specification.
3063 auto **slot = getTrailingObjects<FunctionDecl *>();
3064 slot[0] = epi.ExceptionSpec.SourceDecl;
3065 slot[1] = epi.ExceptionSpec.SourceTemplate;
3066 // This exception specification doesn't make the type dependent, because
3067 // it's not instantiated as part of instantiating the type.
3068 } else if (getExceptionSpecType() == EST_Unevaluated) {
3069 // Store the function decl from which we will resolve our
3070 // exception specification.
3071 auto **slot = getTrailingObjects<FunctionDecl *>();
3072 slot[0] = epi.ExceptionSpec.SourceDecl;
3073 }
3074
3075 // If this is a canonical type, and its exception specification is dependent,
3076 // then it's a dependent type. This only happens in C++17 onwards.
3077 if (isCanonicalUnqualified()) {
3078 if (getExceptionSpecType() == EST_Dynamic ||
3079 getExceptionSpecType() == EST_DependentNoexcept) {
3080 assert(hasDependentExceptionSpec() && "type should not be canonical");
3081 setDependent();
3082 }
3083 } else if (getCanonicalTypeInternal()->isDependentType()) {
3084 // Ask our canonical type whether our exception specification was dependent.
3085 setDependent();
3086 }
3087
3088 // Fill in the extra parameter info if present.
3089 if (epi.ExtParameterInfos) {
3090 auto *extParamInfos = getTrailingObjects<ExtParameterInfo>();
3091 for (unsigned i = 0; i != getNumParams(); ++i)
3092 extParamInfos[i] = epi.ExtParameterInfos[i];
3093 }
3094
3095 if (epi.TypeQuals.hasNonFastQualifiers()) {
3096 FunctionTypeBits.HasExtQuals = 1;
3097 *getTrailingObjects<Qualifiers>() = epi.TypeQuals;
3098 } else {
3099 FunctionTypeBits.HasExtQuals = 0;
3100 }
3101}

3103bool FunctionProtoType::hasDependentExceptionSpec() const {
3104 if (Expr *NE = getNoexceptExpr())
3105 return NE->isValueDependent();
3106 for (QualType ET : exceptions())
3107 // A pack expansion with a non-dependent pattern is still dependent,
3108 // because we don't know whether the pattern is in the exception spec
3109 // or not (that depends on whether the pack has 0 expansions).
3110 if (ET->isDependentType() || ET->getAs<PackExpansionType>())
3111 return true;
3112 return false;
3113}
3114
3115bool FunctionProtoType::hasInstantiationDependentExceptionSpec() const {
3116 if (Expr *NE = getNoexceptExpr())
3117 return NE->isInstantiationDependent();
3118 for (QualType ET : exceptions())
3119 if (ET->isInstantiationDependentType())
3120 return true;
3121 return false;
3122}

3124CanThrowResult FunctionProtoType::canThrow() const {
3125 switch (getExceptionSpecType()) {
3126 case EST_Unparsed:
3127 case EST_Unevaluated:
3128 case EST_Uninstantiated:
3129 llvm_unreachable("should not call this with unresolved exception specs");
3130
3131 case EST_DynamicNone:
3132 case EST_BasicNoexcept:
3133 case EST_NoexceptTrue:
3134 case EST_NoThrow:
3135 return CT_Cannot;
3136
3137 case EST_None:
3138 case EST_MSAny:
3139 case EST_NoexceptFalse:
3140 return CT_Can;
3141
3142 case EST_Dynamic:
3143 // A dynamic exception specification is throwing unless every exception
3144 // type is an (unexpanded) pack expansion type.
3145 for (unsigned I = 0; I != getNumExceptions(); ++I)
3146 if (!getExceptionType(I)->getAs<PackExpansionType>())
3147 return CT_Can;
3148 return CT_Dependent;
3149
3150 case EST_DependentNoexcept:
3151 return CT_Dependent;
3152 }
3153
3154 llvm_unreachable("unexpected exception specification kind");
3155}

3164
3165void FunctionProtoType::Profile(llvm::FoldingSetNodeID &ID, QualType Result,
3166 const QualType *ArgTys, unsigned NumParams,
3167 const ExtProtoInfo &epi,
3168 const ASTContext &Context, bool Canonical) {
3169 // We have to be careful not to get ambiguous profile encodings.
3170 // Note that valid type pointers are never ambiguous with anything else.
3171 //
3172 // The encoding grammar begins:
3173 // type type* bool int bool
3174 // If that final bool is true, then there is a section for the EH spec:
3175 // bool type*
3176 // This is followed by an optional "consumed argument" section of the
3177 // same length as the first type sequence:
3178 // bool*
3179 // Finally, we have the ext info and trailing return type flag:
3180 // int bool
3181 //
3182 // There is no ambiguity between the consumed arguments and an empty EH
3183 // spec because of the leading 'bool' which unambiguously indicates
3184 // whether the following bool is the EH spec or part of the arguments.
3185
3186 ID.AddPointer(Result.getAsOpaquePtr());
3187 for (unsigned i = 0; i != NumParams; ++i)
3188 ID.AddPointer(ArgTys[i].getAsOpaquePtr());
3189 // This method is relatively performance sensitive, so as a performance
3190 // shortcut, use one AddInteger call instead of four for the next four
3191 // fields.
3192 assert(!(unsigned(epi.Variadic) & ~1) &&
3193 !(unsigned(epi.RefQualifier) & ~3) &&
3194 !(unsigned(epi.ExceptionSpec.Type) & ~15) &&
3195 "Values larger than expected.");
3196 ID.AddInteger(unsigned(epi.Variadic) +
3197 (epi.RefQualifier << 1) +
3198 (epi.ExceptionSpec.Type << 3));
3199 ID.Add(epi.TypeQuals);
3200 if (epi.ExceptionSpec.Type == EST_Dynamic) {
3201 for (QualType Ex : epi.ExceptionSpec.Exceptions)
3202 ID.AddPointer(Ex.getAsOpaquePtr());
3203 } else if (isComputedNoexcept(epi.ExceptionSpec.Type)) {
3204 epi.ExceptionSpec.NoexceptExpr->Profile(ID, Context, Canonical);
3205 } else if (epi.ExceptionSpec.Type == EST_Uninstantiated ||
3206 epi.ExceptionSpec.Type == EST_Unevaluated) {
3207 ID.AddPointer(epi.ExceptionSpec.SourceDecl->getCanonicalDecl());
3208 }
3209 if (epi.ExtParameterInfos) {
3210 for (unsigned i = 0; i != NumParams; ++i)
3211 ID.AddInteger(epi.ExtParameterInfos[i].getOpaqueValue());
3212 }
3213 epi.ExtInfo.Profile(ID);
3214 ID.AddBoolean(epi.HasTrailingReturn);
3215}
3216
3217void FunctionProtoType::Profile(llvm::FoldingSetNodeID &ID,
3218 const ASTContext &Ctx) {
3219 Profile(ID, getReturnType(), param_type_begin(), getNumParams(),
3220 getExtProtoInfo(), Ctx, isCanonicalUnqualified());
3221}

3331 std::vector<const RecordType*> RecordTypeList;
3332 RecordTypeList.push_back(this);
3333 unsigned NextToCheckIndex = 0;
3334
3335 while (RecordTypeList.size() > NextToCheckIndex) {
3336 for (FieldDecl *FD :
3337 RecordTypeList[NextToCheckIndex]->getDecl()->fields()) {
3338 QualType FieldTy = FD->getType();
3339 if (FieldTy.isConstQualified())
3340 return true;
3341 FieldTy = FieldTy.getCanonicalType();
3342 if (const auto *FieldRecTy = FieldTy->getAs<RecordType>()) {
3343 if (llvm::find(RecordTypeList, FieldRecTy) == RecordTypeList.end())
3344 RecordTypeList.push_back(FieldRecTy);
3345 }
3346 }
3347 ++NextToCheckIndex;
3348 }
3349 return false;
3350}

3352bool AttributedType::isQualifier() const {
3353 // FIXME: Generate this with TableGen.
3354 switch (getAttrKind()) {
3355 // These are type qualifiers in the traditional C sense: they annotate
3356 // something about a specific value/variable of a type. (They aren't
3357 // always part of the canonical type, though.)
3358 case attr::ObjCGC:
3359 case attr::ObjCOwnership:
3360 case attr::ObjCInertUnsafeUnretained:
3361 case attr::TypeNonNull:
3362 case attr::TypeNullable:
3363 case attr::TypeNullUnspecified:
3364 case attr::LifetimeBound:
3365 case attr::AddressSpace:
3366 case attr::CHERICapability:
3367 case attr::MemoryAddress:
3368 return true;
3369
3370 // All other type attributes aren't qualifiers; they rewrite the modified
3371 // type to be a semantically different type.
3372 default:
3373 return false;
3374 }
3375}

3463 InstantiationDependent = true;

3473TemplateSpecializationType::
3474TemplateSpecializationType(TemplateName T,
3475 ArrayRef<TemplateArgument> Args,
3476 QualType Canon, QualType AliasedType)
3477 : Type(TemplateSpecialization,
3478 Canon.isNull()? QualType(this, 0) : Canon,
3479 Canon.isNull()? true : Canon->isDependentType(),
3480 Canon.isNull()? true : Canon->isInstantiationDependentType(),
3481 false,
3482 T.containsUnexpandedParameterPack()), Template(T) {
3483 TemplateSpecializationTypeBits.NumArgs = Args.size();
3484 TemplateSpecializationTypeBits.TypeAlias = !AliasedType.isNull();
3485
3486 assert(!T.getAsDependentTemplateName() &&
3487 "Use DependentTemplateSpecializationType for dependent template-name");
3488 assert((T.getKind() == TemplateName::Template ||
3489 T.getKind() == TemplateName::SubstTemplateTemplateParm ||
3490 T.getKind() == TemplateName::SubstTemplateTemplateParmPack) &&
3491 "Unexpected template name for TemplateSpecializationType");
3492
3493 auto *TemplateArgs = reinterpret_cast<TemplateArgument *>(this + 1);
3494 for (const TemplateArgument &Arg : Args) {
3495 // Update instantiation-dependent and variably-modified bits.
3496 // If the canonical type exists and is non-dependent, the template
3497 // specialization type can be non-dependent even if one of the type
3498 // arguments is. Given:
3499 // template<typename T> using U = int;
3500 // U<T> is always non-dependent, irrespective of the type T.
3501 // However, U<Ts> contains an unexpanded parameter pack, even though
3502 // its expansion (and thus its desugared type) doesn't.
3503 if (Arg.isInstantiationDependent())
3504 setInstantiationDependent();
3505 if (Arg.getKind() == TemplateArgument::Type &&
3506 Arg.getAsType()->isVariablyModifiedType())
3507 setVariablyModified();
3508 if (Arg.containsUnexpandedParameterPack())
3509 setContainsUnexpandedParameterPack();
3510 new (TemplateArgs++) TemplateArgument(Arg);
3511 }
3512
3513 // Store the aliased type if this is a type alias template specialization.
3514 if (isTypeAlias()) {
3515 auto *Begin = reinterpret_cast<TemplateArgument *>(this + 1);
3516 *reinterpret_cast<QualType*>(Begin + getNumArgs()) = AliasedType;
3517 }
3518}
